Alright, so I've looked up some definitions and explanations of strategic management. From what I've gathered, strategic management is essentially about setting goals and figuring out how to achieve them in a way that gives the organization a competitive edge. It seems like it's more focused on long-term activities because it involves planning for the future and making decisions that will affect the company over an extended period.

For example, one source mentioned that strategic management includes setting objectives, analyzing the competitive environment, and evaluating strategies. These activities sound like they're geared towards looking ahead and preparing for what's to come, rather than dealing with immediate, day-to-day issues.

Another point that stood out is that strategic management isn't just about planning; it's also about implementing those plans and monitoring their effectiveness. So, it's a continuous process that involves not only thinking about the future but also taking action and adjusting strategies as needed.

I also noticed that some sources differentiate between strategic management and operational management. Operational management seems to handle the short-term, day-to-day functions of the business, while strategic management deals with the bigger picture and long-term direction.

